        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(codex): suppress raw commentary echo when phase field is absent",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nIn WebChat direct conversations with Codex-backed providers (e.g. `openai-codex/gpt-5.4`), internal commentary text such as `\"commentary to=functions.browser ...\"` and browser tool-call debug fragments leaked into the user-visible chat bubble.\n\nThe root cause was in the Codex app-server event projector's `handleRawResponseItemCompleted`. When a typed commentary item completed (incrementing `pendingRawCommentaryEchoes`), the paired raw response echo from the Codex app-server could arrive **without** a `phase` field. The suppression guard only matched when `phase === \"commentary\"`, so the un-phased raw item fell through — its text was stored without a phase annotation in `assistantPhaseByItem`, and `resolveFinalAssistantTextItem` included it in the visible reply because `undefined !== \"commentary\"`.\n\nThe fix adds a conservative fallback: when `pendingRawCommentaryEchoes > 0` but the raw item has no `phase`, the raw item is also suppressed. This matches the existing deduplication contract — one typed commentary echo consumes one raw counterpart.\n\nFixes #89668\n\n## What Problem This Solves\n\nCodex model turns that use the browser tool generate commentary text describing the tool call. This text is internal scaffolding and should never be visible to end users. When it leaks, it pollutes assistant replies with confusing/embarrassing garbage and can make it look like OpenClaw inserted ads into the answer.\n\n## Evidence\n\nThe fix adds 2 lines of logic + tests. The existing test suite for Codex comment echo deduplication covers the happy path (raw item WITH phase). The new test verifies the fix for the edge case (raw item WITHOUT phase).\n\nBefore the fix:\n- Typed commentary completion echoes as preamble ✅\n- Raw echo WITH `phase: \"commentary\"` is suppressed ✅  \n- Raw echo WITHOUT `phase` field leaks ❌ → **BUG**\n\nAfter the fix:\n- All three cases correctly suppress the echo\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior addressed**: Raw commentary echoes shipped without a `phase` field by the Codex app-server leaked into visible assistant text, appearing in WebChat as `\"commentary to=functions.browser\"` and tool-call scaffolding fragments.\n\n**Real setup tested**:\n- **Runtime**: Node.js v24.13.1, Linux x86_64\n- **Test framework**: Vitest v4.1.8\n- **Branch**: `fix/issue-89668`\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch**:\n\n```bash\ncd /home/0668001085/workspace/openclaw\ngit checkout fix/issue-89668\nnpx vitest run extensions/codex/src/app-server/event-projector.test.ts\n```\n\n**After-fix evidence**:\n\nThe key code change in `extensions/codex/src/app-server/event-projector.ts`:\n\n```typescript\n// FIX #89668: The Codex app-server may ship raw response echoes for\n// commentary items without a phase field.  When a typed commentary\n// completion was already echoed, conservatively suppress the paired\n// raw item even when its phase is absent, so the commentary text\n// cannot leak into visible assistant output.\nif (!phase && this.pendingRawCommentaryEchoes > 0) {\n  this.pendingRawCommentaryEchoes -= 1;\n  return;\n}\n```\n\nTest scenario verified:\n```typescript\n// Typed commentary completion → pendingRawCommentaryEchoes = 1\n// Raw response echo without phase → suppressed (FIX)\n// Later raw-only note → delivered normally\nexpect(preambles.map(event => event.data.progressText)).toEqual([\n  \"Checking the workspace\",  // typed echo\n  \"Still working\",           // distinct later note\n]);\n```\n\n**Observed result after the fix**: Raw commentary echoes missing a `phase` field are consumed by the existing echo counter instead of falling through to `assistantTextByItem`. Commentary text stays hidden. Distinct raw-only notes after the echo are still delivered correctly.\n\n**What was not tested**: Live WebChat session with Codex + browser tool against a real endpoint. The fix is at the event-projection layer; it corrects a deterministic counter-mismatch that is reproducible in unit tests.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\n**Did user-visible behavior change?** `No` — only removes leaked commentary text that should never have been visible. All correctly-phased commentary items continue to be suppressed as before.\n\n**Did config, environment, or migration behavior change?** `No`.\n\n**Did security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change?** `No`.\n\n**What is the highest-risk area?** The conservative suppression could theoretically eat a raw response item that was NOT a commentary echo if the counter was incremented by a different mechanism.\n\n**How is that risk mitigated?** `pendingRawCommentaryEchoes` is only incremented by the typed `agentMessage` commentary completion handler (line 659), and only for items with `phase: \"commentary\"`. Each increment has an exact 1:1 correspondence with a raw echo. The suppression only triggers when the counter is positive, matching the existing contract.\n\n## Current review state\n\n**What is the next action?** Maintainer review requested.",
